## Abstract

This dissertation presents the complete formal theory of the P-Model Compiler—a mathematically rigorous framework for transforming constrained optimization problems into quantum-ready QUBO formulations with provable guarantees. Unlike traditional penalty methods that require heuristic λ-tuning, our approach derives penalties directly from the problem structure using spectral gap analysis and Lipschitz continuity arguments. We prove that the P-Model encoding achieves $O(N \log N)$ connectivity vs. $O(N^2)$ in traditional methods, with formal bounds on variable inflation and constraint satisfaction. The theory encompasses: (1) the Algebraic P-Model Encoding Theorem establishing optimal ancilla complexity; (2) the Spectral Gap Lemma guaranteeing ground state preservation; (3) the Treewidth Reduction Theorem enabling efficient hardware embedding; (4) the Theory of Refusal providing formal safety guarantees; and (5) the Stability Theory ensuring hardware noise resilience. All results are proven mathematically without reliance on empirical validation, establishing the compiler as a formally verified bridge between NP-hard optimization and quantum annealing hardware.

