6. **Refusal Theory (Chapter 5):** Provided formal safety guarantees for autonomous systems.

### 11.2 The Topology-Precision Trade-off

The core insight of this dissertation is the **Topology-Precision Trade-off**:

- Traditional QUBO: Minimize variables → maximize connectivity ($K_N$ cliques)
- P-Model: Maximize variables (ancilla) → minimize connectivity (logarithmic treewidth)

**Theorem 11.1 (Industrial Scaling).** There exists a crossover point $N_c$ (typically $N \approx 8$) beyond which the P-Model always requires fewer physical couplers than a minor-embedded $K_N$ graph on any planar or near-planar QPU.

*Proof.* The number of couplers in P-Model is $O(N \log N)$. The number of physical qubits required to embed $K_N$ on a planar graph is $\Omega(N^2)$. Thus for sufficiently large $N$, $O(N \log N) < \Omega(N^2)$. ∎

### 11.3 Final Statement

The Industrial QUBO Compiler is now mathematically defined as a system that transforms an NP-hard specification into a **Topologically Sparse Hamiltonian** while preserving the **Semantic Ground State**. The success of this work lies in the **Reduction of Treewidth**—moving from the $O(N)$ treewidth of "brute-force" penalty methods to the $O(\log N)$ treewidth of hierarchical P-Model gadgets. This is the difference between a problem that is "Quantum Theoretical" and one that is "Quantum Manufacturable."

The quantum AI race will be won by compiler engineers, but only when armed with rigorous mathematical foundations like those presented here. This dissertation provides those foundations, establishing the P-Model Compiler as a formally verified bridge between NP-hard optimization and quantum annealing hardware.

